192
20:54.330 --> 20:59.160
It's just a convenient and precise way of describing this string.

193
20:59.160 --> 21:06.180
Once again, when we're
working with the query model, we aren't worrying about how
to implement these query gates.

194
21:06.180 --> 21:11.310
That's the same issue
we had with query gates for Boolean circuit.

195
21:11.310 --> 21:19.950
It's not our job to prepare the input, we're given the input in the
form of these query gates.

196
21:19.950 --> 21:28.230
I will point out though, that if we know how to
implement the function f using a Boolean circuit, then it is possible to
translate that implementation

197
21:28.230 --> 21:37.890
pretty directly to a quantum
circuit implementation of Uf, and we'll see exactly how
that works in the next lesson.

198
21:37.890 --> 21:47.460
As an aside, it is quite straightforward to create a Boolean circuit
that operates like this, using a single classical
query gate for the function f,

199
21:47.460 --> 21:53.490
but that is quite different from having a quantum
circuit implementation of this unitary gate.

200
21:53.490 --> 22:00.300
The point, however, is that
for classical query algorithms, having a query gate that works like this is, in fact, equivalent

201
22:00.300 --> 22:07.470
to having an ordinary
classical query gate for f, in the sense that either one can be implemented using the other.

202
22:07.470 --> 22:16.200
In this section of the lesson, we'll discuss Deutsch's algorithm, which is a very simple
quantum query algorithm, but it really is a gem.

203
22:16.200 --> 22:26.820
This algorithm comes from a 1985 paper written by David Deutsch, was one of the very first people to work on the theoretical
foundations of quantum computing.

204
22:26.820 --> 22:32.903
The algorithm itself represents a very small part
of Deutsch's 1985 paper, and in fact,

205
22:32.903 --> 22:38.940
the algorithm we now
call Deutsch's algorithm is actually an improved version of the algorithm that Deutsch described.

206
22:38.940 --> 22:46.320
It provides a very modest example of how quantum computers can
offer computational advantages, but you have to start somewhere,

207
22:46.320 --> 22:50.820
and it really was an important spark that got things started.

208
22:50.820 --> 22:57.660
Deutsch's algorithm solves a query problem that's often called Deutsch's problem in the context of quantum computing,

209
22:57.660 --> 23:07.860
but in fact, it's none other
than the parity problem for functions from one bit to one bit, which we've already talked about.

210
23:07.860 --> 23:16.920
As we've already seen, there are four functions
from one bit to one bit, and they're described here on the screen by their tables of values.

211
23:16.920 --> 23:24.450
The first and last of these
functions are constant, while the middle two are balanced in the sense that the two
possible output values

212
23:24.450 --> 23:28.080
appear the same number of times.

213
23:28.080 --> 23:36.300
For the two constant functions,
we see that the parity, or in other words, the eXclusive OR of the two outputs is 0,

214
23:36.300 --> 23:42.848
and for the two balance functions, the parity of the outputs is 1.

215
23:42.848 --> 23:49.710
So an equivalent way to
describe the parity problem in this particular case, where the function f takes
a single bit as input,

216
23:49.710 --> 23:54.300
or in other words, Deutsch's problem, is like you see here.

217
23:54.300 --> 24:00.660
The input is a function f
from one bit to one bit, and the output is 0 if f is constant

218
24:00.660 --> 24:06.240
and 1 if f is balanced.

219
24:06.240 --> 24:14.130
As I've already suggested, every classical query algorithm
that solves this problem must make at least two queries to f.

220
24:14.130 --> 24:22.080
If you learn just one of
the two output values of f, you still have no information at all about the parity of the two outputs.

221
24:22.080 --> 24:27.900
And this, by the way, is true
even for classical algorithms that make use of randomness.

222
24:27.900 --> 24:34.950
Randomness can sometimes be very useful for solving query problems, and we'll see an example
a bit later in the lesson,

223
24:34.950 --> 24:39.420
but randomness doesn't help here.

224
24:39.420 --> 24:46.590
So our algorithm from before is optimal among classical query algorithms
for Deutsch's problem.

225
24:46.590 --> 24:54.930
Now we'll take a look
at Deutsche's algorithm, which is a quantum query algorithm that solves Deutsch's
problem using a single query.

226
24:54.930 --> 24:59.580
And here is the algorithm
described as a quantum circuit.

227
24:59.580 --> 25:08.190
We have two qubits
initialized like you see here, with the top one initialized to cat 0 and the bottom one initialized to cat 1,

228
25:08.190 --> 25:13.020
and we'll see why we initialize these qubits like this shortly.

229
25:13.020 --> 25:20.190
We perform Hadamard
gates on the two qubits, feed them into the query gate, perform another Hadamard
gate on the top qubit,

230
25:20.190 --> 25:31.860
and then measure it. And the claim is that
the measurement outcome gives us, with certainty, the
correct answer to the problem.

231
25:31.860 --> 25:38.160
So let's analyze the
circuit one step at a time to see exactly how it works.

232
25:38.160 --> 25:45.930
The state of the two qubits after the first layer of Hadamard gates is the tensor product of
the minus and plus states.

233
25:45.930 --> 25:54.300
The Hadamard on top maps
the 0 state to a plus state, and the Hadamard on the bottom maps the 1 state to a minus state.

234
25:54.300 --> 25:59.940
The top qubit is on the right, and the bottom qubit is on the left, so this is the state that we get.

235
25:59.940 --> 26:06.663
It's very important that the bottom qubit is in a minus state, by the way, this wouldn't work if we
initialize the bottom qubit

236
26:06.663 --> 26:09.900
to a 0 state instead of a 1 state.

237
26:09.900 --> 26:14.190
We're going to expand this state
halfway, like you see here.

238
26:14.190 --> 26:22.260
The reason for doing that
isn't clear at this point, but it will be convenient
in just a moment.

239
26:22.260 --> 26:28.080
Next, let's think about
the state of the two qubits after the query gate is performed.

240
26:28.080 --> 26:36.120
The way the query gate
works is that it computes F on the standard basis
state of the top qubit and XOR is the value
onto the bottom qubit,

